arXiv:2606.15166v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: The decays $ ar{B}ightarrow D^*	au^{-} ar{
u}_	au$ provide sensitive probes of new physics in the $bightarrow c	au
u$ transition. We discuss the effects of new physics in the decay chain $ ar{B}ightarrow D^*(ightarrow D\pi)	au^{-}(ightarrow V^-
u_	au) ar{
u}_	au$ where $V$ is a vector meson. We first present a comprehensive analysis of the five-dimensional angular distribution for the full decay chain $ ar{B}ightarrow D^*(ightarrow D\pi)	au^{-}(ightarrow ho^-
u_	au) ar{
u}_	au$, exploiting the hadronic $	au$ decay to $ho^-
u_	au$ to circumvent the experimental challenge of direct $	au$ reconstruction. The differential decay rate is expressed in terms of measurable kinematic variables $	heta^*$, $E_ho$, $	heta_ho$, $\chi_ho$, and $q^2$ -- with complete coefficient functions provided for scalar, pseudoscalar, vector, axialvector, and tensor new-physics interactions. From this distribution we construct a set of integrated observables, including the $D^*$ polarization fractions and lepton-side forward-backward and azimuthal asymmetries, which isolate distinct combinations of helicity amplitudes. We further perform a numerical analysis using current experimental data on $R_{D^*}$ and the $D^*$ longitudinal polarization fraction $\langle F_L^{D^*}angle$ to constrain the complex new-physics couplings $g_L$, $g_R$, $g_P$, and $g_T$, revealing the correlations among them. Our formalism is also applicable to $	au 	o a_1 
u_	au$, where the $3\pi$ final states mainly come from the $a_1$ meson. The framework established here provides a powerful tool for disentangling new-physics scenarios with future high-statistics data.
